column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While in the process of moving freight at the BAX Global facility, there was a forklift puncture to one (1) fiberboard box of Alcohols, n.o.s., which resulted in the release of approximately 1 liter of product.  The free product was contained to the facility floor at the BAX Global, Inc. HUB facility.  Dave Owen of BAX Global, Inc. performed cleanup with the use of gloves and plastic bags, and applied absorbent pads and speedy dry to the free liquid.  The spent absorbents, speedy dry, and cleanup materials were containerized into one(1) 30-gallon steel recovery drum, along with the damaged container.  BAX Global, Inc. will coordinate disposition of the one (1) 30-gallon recovery drum, in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a forklift puncture, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  BAX Global will continue to reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: Container was tendered to Horizon Lines as non-hazardous, TOLU381070-6/CA2048779, to be loaded on the KO712N. During a random pre-load inspection, it was discovered that it contained a vehicle with more then 1/4 tank of gas. Shipper was notified for correction to paperwork, and arrangemnets were made to remove enough gas to meet the limit of 1/4 tank. Due to the time needed to get corrected hazmat paperwork and address the fuel level, this shipment was rolled to AZ724N, to be loaded 7/11/08 for transit to Anchorage.

column26: Int'l Trade Ctr. 300 Waterloo Valley Rd.
column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While at the Triple Crown Services facility in Calumet Park, Illinois free product was discovered leaking from the rail car. Approximately 15 gallons of free product were released. The release was due to a faulty seal on a valve. SET Environmental, Inc. of Bridgeview, Illinois was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  SET Environmental, Inc. applied absorbent material as needed, and proceeded to pump the remaining product from the leaking tote.  The product was pumped into seven (7) 55-gallon drums.  SET Environmental, Inc. will coordinate disposal of the waste generated as a result of the incident.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH NOT LESS THAN 20 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 40 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling on Interstate 80 eastbound, approximately 20 miles east of Joliet, Illinois, the load shifted in transit, which resulted in a leak from the portable tank.  Approximately 330 gallons of hydrogen peroxide aqueous solution were released.  The Tinley Park Fire Department responded to assess the site.  Upon arrival, free product was detected along the asphalt roadway, and eastbound lane of the Interstate was closed, pending cleanup.  The Tinley Park Fire Department Hazmat Division was dispatched to perform the cleanup, which involved the application of water to neutralize the product, and dilute the concentrated material.  Tinley Park Fire Department Hazmat Division washed the product from the area, upon neutralization, and no further cleanup was required.  Highway lane was reopened to trafffic after approximately 2 hours.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to the load shifting in transit, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Webb Chemical Company will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: On July 2, 2008 date at 12:40 EST, personnel in the CSXT Lansing Michigan Yard discovered PLMX 4619, a residue tank car of Anhydrous Ammonia, leaking from the top of the tank car. The car was isolated and shipper, local, state and/or federal agencies were notified (CHEMTREC Report #2008-07-02-00125). Youngs Environmental, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a small vapor leak from the A-end liquid line valve plug.  The angle valve was closed but the plug was not tool tight. Contractor personnel removed the plug, opened and closed the valve and the vapor release had stopped.  They reinstalled the plug tool tight. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move.  Cause Code:  120  NARRI:  5 (4+9+0) X (2+0) = 130

column168: Trailer was charged with air pressure in order to unload. 45 minutes into the unloading process the plant operator noticed a drip develope on the trailer belly just forward of the front axle. The operator placed a catch pale under the drip. About the same time of the discovery of the drip the driver was directed by the operator to shut down. Their storage tank was full. Once the air pressure in the trailer was released the drip stopped.  The trailer was not empty and the ballance of the material was delivered the following day with out a leak.  The trailer was cleaned, repaired, tested and placed back in service.  It was found that the trailer had several pits, two of which were through holes.
column169: The driver had nothing to do with thie incident.  The carrier has put tighter ph restrictions on the products we transport.   After a repair has been made to the inside of a trailer barrel the trailer will be passivated prior to its use.

column168: On July 9, 2008 at 11:55, personnel in the CSX Transportation, Willard, OH yard discovered TILX 195234, a loaded tank car of Alcohol, NOS, leaking from its top. The car was isolated. T. J. Mannas, Manager-Hazardous Materials Field Services, CSX Transportation inspected TILX 195234. He noted evidence of a leak beween the manway cover and its nozzle. All manway cover bolts were found to be more than hand tight. T. J. Mannas inspected the six manway cover bolts for securement with an 18 inch pipe wrench. He noted some bolts were tigher than others (The bolts appeared to be have been tightened in a circular pattern as opposed to a star method). He broke seal (SEALED 2184035) on the manway cover. He inspected outage and found it to be adequate, 5.25 inches. The gasket and its seats were in proper condition for transportation. He reseated the manway cover and tightened the six manway cover bolts in a star pattern, making five complete sequential tightenings of these bolts, using an 18 inch pipe wrench, and the leak ceased. T. J. Mannas sealed the manway with CSX Transportation HazMat seal # 1030. TILX 195234 was monitored by CSX Transportation personnel prior to its departure from Willard, OH. T. J. Mannas discussed the condition of TILX 195234 as he had found it with shipper's representative,  Mr. Larry Wilson, Plant Manager, Cargill, Inc., Bloomingburg, OH for his corrective action.  NARRI: 5(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80 ; Cause Code 200

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While unloading at the Roadrunner Dawes Freight Systems, Inc. facility in Irving, Texas, a leak was discovered in the trailer.  Apparently, one (1) 55-gallon drum had a cracked bottom, which caused the drum to release its contents inside the trailer.  Cactus Environmental Services of Dallas, Texas was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, Cactus Environmental Services applied absorbent material to the free liquid, and recovered the spent material from the trailer floor.  Cactus Environmental Services proceeded to pressure wash the trailer floor to remove residual staining.  The spent material and cleanup debris were placed into one (1) 55-gallon drum, pending disposal.  The damaged drum was overpacked into one (1) 85-gallon drum.  Disposal will be coordinated by Cactus Environmental Services in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to packaging failure, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Roadrunner Dawes Freight Systems, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

At the consignee the operator was attempting to remove the three inch dust cap from the three inch product discharge valve and for three attempts there was product   behind the cap. The operator discontinued the attempt and rejected the trailer.  The trailer was transported to the motor carrier terminal and at the tank wash the cap was removed and a minimal amount of product was captured. It was determined at that time that because the trailer was bottom loaded maybe the operator at the shipping point failed to drain the material properly from the outlet leg prior to shipment leaving the line full.  The trailer was rescheduled for shipment and delivery was made.  Trailer was cleaned and tested and it was determined that the internal valve needed a new gasket. After repair a vacuume test on both the internal and external valves and passed.
column169: Norminally during bottom loading the wet lines are draine of residual product. The internal vale was teasted and showed to be leaking by but the external valve was not. The question at this time still remaines as to how the material got to the dust cap. It is possible that after loading the line was not drained and material became traped between the external valve seat and the dust cap.

On File Number 22710, on July 15, 2008, a Quality Carriers tractor-tanker was involved in a release of hazardous resin solution, UN1866.  Approximately 70 gallons of solution was released from the fill cap of the tank.  The product impacted an area of asphalt approximately 10ft x 50ft and a second location approximately 5ft x 15ft.  ERTS dispatched a contractor to the site to perform cleanup and remediation activities.  When UST Environmental personnel arrived on scene, they began an initial size up of the project.  The released material had already dried on the asphalt surface when the contractor arrived.  The contractor applied a light dusting of granular absorbents to the impacted areas of asphalt and ground them into the surface to remove any residual product.  It was determined that there was no free product remaining on the site and clean up efforts were complete.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste staged at the intended waste management facility’s in transit storage facility pending receipt and processing. Facility personnel activated the facility’s emergency response team and entered the van trailer after first donning appropriate personal protective equipment.  The response team identified 2 containers that had developed a small leak allowing approximately 2 gallons of material to escape from the package.  The containers in question were placed into suitable salvage drums and the trailer was moved to the facility’s processing area where the load was accepted and disposed of.  Facility personnel cleaned the inside of the van trailer with a suitable cleaning compound and containerized the contaminated soil where the material escaped from the trailer.  This material was also disposed of at the facility where the release was identified.

column169: On The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR), shippers are immediately notified of all HAZMAT releases.  For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package or closure defects), where possible, shippers (responsible party) are requested to respond, repair and remediate.  By immediately involving the shipper, in-depth knowledge of the release cause is gained by the same organization that can implement process changes to prevent recurrence.  After each NAR incident, KCSR provides outreach to the shipper to help investigate root-cause factors for correction.  For non-accident related releases, the shipper should be contacted directly for details associated with actions taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While unloading, free product was discovered inside of the trailer.  Roadrunner Dawes Freight Systems, Inc. personnel applied absorbent material to contain the free liquid.  AMX Environmental Evolution, LTD of Dallas, Texas was dispatched to perform the cleanup.    AMX Environmental Evolution, LTD investigated the trailer and discovered two (2) damaged 55-gallon drums.  Approximately 50-gallons combined released from the two drums and contaminated additional freight. Apparently the damage was the result of the freight being crushed due to improper loading.  AMX Environmental Evolution, LTD applied additional absorbent material as needed and removed all of the contaminated pallets and freight.  The two (2) damaged drums were each placed into one (1) 55-gallon overpack drum.  The contaminated absorbent materials were placed into five (5) 55-gallon recovery drums.  The contaminated pallets and freight were placed into a roll-off box.  AMX Environmental Evolution LTD will coordinate disposal of the waste generated as a result of the incident.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.  However, Roadrunner Dawes Freight Systems, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  Prior to being accepted for processing, the shipment was staged at the facility’s in-transit storage area.  While pending receipt, facility personnel observed a small amount of liquid dripping from the rear door of a van trailer.  Emergency Response personnel entered the trailer using appropriate personal protective equipment and determined that a polyethylene IBC developed a small leak from the body of the container that allowed approximately 3 gallons of material to leak onto the floor of the van trailer.  The crew immediately contained the release and moved the compromised container to the facility’s waste management area where the contents of the container were removed and processed.  The response crew then absorbed all free liquids with a suitable absorbent material and containerized the clean-up debris in a suitable container.  This material was placed into storage pending disposal at a licensed waste management facility.
column169: At the time of loading, the driver inspected the container and did not observe any evidence of leakage or damage to the container.  The individuals that responded to the release did indicate that it is suspected that the leak developed during transport and was suspected to be caused by either age or degradation of the container over time.  In order to prevent a recurrence, the shipper has been advised as to the suspected cause of the release and has been asked to insure that all containers are thoroughly inspected prior to being offered for transportation.  In addition, the driver has been reinstructed to insure any container of questionable integrity is thoroughly inspected prior to accepting for transport.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the shipment was placed into temporary storage for the purpose of consolidating a less than truck load quantity of non bulk packages into a full truck load.  During the transfer operation, a 55 gallon drum slipped off the drum dolly and was punctured by the support forks of the dolly.  The drum was immediately up righted and the crew responsible for the transfer immediately donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and contained the spill on the concrete dock with an absorbent material.  The damaged container was placed into an 85 gallon salvage drum and loaded onto the van trailer for continued transportation to the intended waste management facility along with a 55 gallon bon bulk package containing the clean-up debris generated as a result of the spill response.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence, all personnel involved in the transfer of these containers were re-instructed on the proper use of drum handling equipment.  It is believed that the cause of the release was attributed to the drum being incorrectly positioned on the dolly allowing it to slip and be punctured by the forks on the bottom of the dolly.

column168: UTLX 202788 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported leaking product from the top fitting area in the railyard. UTLX 202788 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard awaiting a detailed inspection. A BNSF contract responder inspected UTLX 202788 finding the liquid eduction valve not fully closed and product seeping out from around the liquid line's threaded plug. The responder closed the valve (approximately 1/4 turn) using a wrench. The liquid line plug was checked and it was tightened slightly to fully tool tight. Apparently, internal pressure build-up inside UTLX 202788 forced product to seep out from the threaded plug area. All other fittings were checked and deemed secure. Response was concluded by 1900 hrs. CDT 7/02/08 after UTLX 202788 was monitored and no further product release was evident. Product spillage on the tank shell evaporated.  A small product stain under UTLX 202788 was treated with Micro-Blaze.  After UTLX 202788 was unloaded it was directed to a qualified repair facility for further inspection of its valves and fittings.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Operator measured tank to verify inbound bulk load of 5100 gallons of ethanol would fit in storage tank. He mistakenly calulated the innage for a 12,000 gallon tank instead of a 6000 gallon tank. 1000 gallons was transferred into IBCs and drum containers, the balance was pumped into a 6000 gallon tank which already had material in it. column168: A BNSF switch crew reported PROX 42161 (DOT 111A100W6 tank car) leaking product from the manway area during normal switching operations in the railyard and movement of PROX 42161 was stopped. No additional product spillage was evident when PROX 42161 remained motionless. A BNSF mechanical responder immediately inspected PROX 42161 and reported tool tightening four of the eight manway securement bolts. Afterwards, a shipper responder arrived and inspected PROX 42161 finding all valves and fittings secure. PROX 42161 was then moved in the railyard under close observation by the responders. During this movement, a small amount of product was observed emanating from the manway area and movement was stopped. The shipper responder then inspected the manway nozzle gasket. The gasket appeared to be in good condition and undamaged. The responder proceeded to replace this gasket, installing a new gasket and resecured the manway cover. PROX 42161 was again moved in the railyard under responder observation and this time no product release was observed. PROX 42161 was released to proceed to its destination. All spillage evaporated. Response was concluded by 1530 hrs. CDT, 7/02/08.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column169: MAKE SURE THAT FREIGHT IS SHROUDED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED. TOTES CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND OR CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING MTY PALLETS, PLYWOOD AND OR DUNNAGE. AVOID LOADING HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF TOTES, TO PREVENT PRESSURE BUILD-UP, RESULTING IN THE LID OR CAP TO POP OFF. USING DECK BARS OR LOAD LOCK WITH CUSHIONS AND PIECES OF DUNNAGE TO ENSURE A NAIL OR SHARP OBJECT DOES NOT PUNCTURED THE TOTE.RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS. RETRAIN IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING NOTE AND THAT PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT. PROTECT TOTE TANK FROM ADJACENT FREIGHT WITH WOODEN PALLETS AND DUNNAGE.

column42: AMMONIUM NITRATE-FUEL OIL MIXTURE (CONTAINING ONLY PRILLED AMMONIUM NITRATE AND FUEL OIL)
column168: Driver operating a box truck traveling southerly on Maine I-95 (Sidney) was stopped for a  Commercial Vehicle / Driver Inspection. Upon inspecting the cargo, the inspector and driver discovered approximately 1 pound of 'prill'(Ammonium Nitrate with Fuel Oil) isolated to a small area of the truck floor. The original bag had an abrasive tear that occurred during the return run at day end. The bags were still on the original manufacture's pallet and still shrink wrapped. The driver gathered the prills and place the product back into the bag, secured the bag with duct tape and was allowed to continue. See attached photo.
column169: Additional driver training in order to include monitoring of pallett loads prior to departures. In this case identifying potential leaks while in transit was the issue.

column168: During normal switching operations in the railyard, UTLX 812989 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was observed by the BNSF switch crew with liquid product emanating from the top of this tank car during movement and the movement was stopped. UTLX 812989 was cordoned off in the railyard awaiting a detailed inspection by hazardous material responders. BNSF contract and shipper responders inspected UTLX 812989 finding the manway seal as the product release source. All manway securement bolts were found to be tool tight. The manway gasket was inspected and found to be out of position, pinched with a portion of the gasket hanging down into the manway nozzle. Responders replaced the manway gasket with a new gasket and resecured the manway. Securement was completed by 0650 hrs. CDT, 7/08/08. All spillage on the tank shell evaporated and there was no ground impact. No further product release was evident from subsequent rail movements. The shipper requested that UTLX 812989 be returned to them for further evaluation.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A BNSF mechanical carman reported TILX 260336 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) in the railyard leaking product from the manway area. A BNSF hazardous material/mechanical responder immediately inspected TILX 260336 finding 4 of the 8 manway securement bolts less than tool tight (loose about two turns each). The manway gasket was also inspected and it was found to be torn with only half of the gasket surface in the proper position. The responder applied a new gasket and properly secured the manway cover. The spillage on the tank car shell evaporated and no ground impact was evident. Response was concluded by 0840 CDT, 7/09/08.

Skyline Chemical driver was dispatched to deliver 4,000 gallons of Hcl to a well site for production work on the Kemp A Unit on 07-02-2008. The driver was instructed by the fracturing company (Frac Source) to unload the product into a Frac Source transport (capacity 5,400 gal). The Skyline Chemical,lnc. driver was told by Frac Source personnel monitoring the unloading that there was about 1,000 gallons in the transport. The Skyline Chemical driver prepared his trailer for unloading and upon completion notified Frac Source personnel (on site)that the unloading would requireassistance monitoring fluid levels in the receiving tank. Frac Source personnel on location stated they did not have safety equipment available to assist the unloading. So the driver decided he would monitor both tanks while unloading the hcl. The unloading went well until the delivery tank was empty. These particular hcl trailers unload by pressuring the tank to move the liquid from one trailer to next. When the delivering trailers product was unloaded, the pressure it took to transfer it followed. This caused the pressure(10-12 psi) to transfer to the receiving tank. The tank level in the receiving tank (Frac Source) was approximately 3” from being full to capacity. The pressure in the delivery tank caused the fluid in the receiver’s tank to overflow on to location. The spill was quickly neutralized with sodium bicarbonate (soda ashe) by Frac Source and Skyline Chemical personnel.
column169: Receiver should always provide assistance to help monitor fluid levels. A partially filled tank being topped off requiresmonitoring to insure over-filling does not occur.

column168: On July 10, 2008 at 08:40, a CSXT yard crew at Niagara Yard discovered SBLX 14170, a residue tank car of Chlorine, to have an odor of chlorine near the tank car. The car was isolated and the consignee, Olin Corporation, was contacted to respond and investigate the odor.  The Olin Chlorep Team responded to Niagara Yard and found SBLX 14170 to be properly sealed. Upon seal removal, the A-End liquid line and closure plug were less than tool tight. The Olin Chlorep team tightened the valve and plug, decontaminated the protective housing, and rechecked the valve and closure plug for securement. The tank car was dispositioned to Olin Corporations Niagara Falls Buffalo Avenue plant that afternoon for a valve removal and inspection. Chemtrec Report Number 20080710-00072.    Cause Code:  300  narri:  5(4+10+5) x (2+0) = 190

column168: July 21, 2008: At approximately 9:00AM, Conrail crew was switching Pt. Richmond Yard, Philadelphia, PA, and noted tank car UTLX 48501, load Alcohols, NOS (Isononyl Alcohol), leaking from the manway area when under movement.  Car secured on track.    Further inspection by CR emergency response contractor REACT Environmental Services, Inc. found the manway cover gasket was misaligned when the manway was secured after loading, allowing the gasket to pinch and not provide adequate securement.  REACT replaced the inspected gasket with a Viton manway nozzle "boot" gasket and re-secured the manway cover tool tight.  Car okayed for movement to original destination.
column169: Attempts by CR Risk Manager A. Richter to call the waybill-displayed 24-hour emergency response phone number (401-425-8000) proved unsuccessful, and received only a constant busy signal. column168: The shipment was offered under a vessel sharing agreement to NYK Line as non-hazardous cargo by Hapag-Lloyd, on behalf of their shipper, for transport on the NYK Line container vessel Iwato V. 13S29 from New York, New York to Santos, Brasil.    Hapag-Lloyd advised NYK Line after the vessel had sailed from New York of the following hazardous material in the container that was not originally booked or otherwise identified.    - UN3262 CORROSIVE SOLID, BASIC, INORGANIC, N.O.S. (Disodium Trioxosilicate/ Sodium Tetraborate), CL 8, PG III, (LTD QTY)     The shipping papers that accompanied the freight container to the marine terminal did not indicate the presence of the hazardous material, and the container was not placarded and/or marked to reflect the presence of the hazardous item.    Hapag-Lloyd subsequently provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to NYK Line.

column168: Driver opened the internal valve and opened the external valve at which time the material started to leak at the quick connect bonnet assembly. Material spilled into a catch bucket that was placed under the valve. A small amount of material hit the containment pad. Driver closed the internal valve a drained the material into the bucket. The trailer was taken to the carriers terminal and it was determined that the envelope gasket at the quick connect was bad. The gasket was changed out and the material was delivered.
column169: A closer inspection of this gasket by the driver may have prevented this incident but not 100% sure because the shop person had to take it out to descover the problem. The envelope gasket had deteriated over time and had cracked at the fold allowing material to seep through. These gaskets are to be inspected after each time the trailer is washed out.

The car was isolated and CSXT Hazmat Manager Austin  was dispatched to the scene and found one of eight manway bolts less than tool tight. The manway bolt was made tool tight and the bottom outlet assembly was checked with no exceptions noted. Once the manway was secure the car released for transport.    Cause Code:  200  NARRI:  5 (5+1+0) X (2+0) = 60

A BNSF switch crew reported an ammonia odor in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately investigated and sought out the odor source. The responder found PLMX 135299 (DOT 112J340W tank car) as the odor source and then directed it to be isolated in the railyard. Afterwards, the responder reported that PLMX 135299's 280.5 psi pressure relief device (PRD) was emanating a slight product vapor hiss. No liquid spillage was evident. BNSF contract responders arriving from Forth Worth, TX also inspected PLMX 135299 concluding that the PRD was emitting a product odor. The internal pressure of PLMX 135299 was 125 psi and gauged with 16.5 inches of product outage. The responders removed the PRD o-ring cap/retainer and found the seat o-ring (inner o-ring) was partially split or cut, possibly from over compression. A replacement o-ring cap/retainer with new o-rings was installed and secured. Leak detection fluid was used to ensure no further vapor release was present around the PRD. PLMX 135299 was monitored and reinspected at 0715 hrs. CDT, 7/16/08. Internal pressure was holding at 125 psi and no further product odor or vapor release was detectable. PLMX 135299 was released to proceed to its destination.  Specification stencil on PLMX 135299 indicated that the 280.5 psi PRD was qualified in 2003 and due 2008.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported an ammonia odor at the east end of the railyard. All activity in that area was ceased and the area cordoned off. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected the railcars at the location of the reported odor. The responder reported finding PROX 34814 (DOT 112J340W tank car) as the odor source. Seal AGR 078253 was removed from the valve housing cover. The responder then found the liquid valve partially open (1/2 turn to close) and its closure plug not fully tool tight (3/4 turn to close). The responder closed the liquid valve and tool tightened its closure plug. PROX 34814's internal pressure was at 160 psi. The responder also noticed some rust developing inside the valve housing area which is indicative of exposure to a mix of ammonia with moisture. This tank car was new and on its first loaded trip in transportation. The response was concluded by 0635 hrs. CDT, 7/26/08 when no further product odor was evident after the securement was completed. The valve housing was resealed with BNSF seal numbered 002455.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Employee was filling his truck at the SU for the days deliveries. Employee did not use his key loop stayed but stayed with his truck while fueling.  When the gage reached 80% the EE turned off the pump then left the area to grab his cell phone out of the SU building. Employee came back, got in the truck, and started pulled away approx 10 ft.  when he realized something was not right, looked in his mirror and realized he had just pulled away with the hose still connected.  The hose stayed attached and in tact the break occurred where the 30 inch pipe tube meets the riser.  Everything was secured and only 2 gallons max liquid released.
column169: Employees are coached to follow our policies of ignition key control and performing a complete walk-around of the vehicle before moving it. Employees who fail to follow our policies are often times required to write and present a safety meeting to their peers covering the infraction they committed. A pull-away is regarded as a very serious offense, therefore have a greater potential for more severe disciplinary actions.

column168: During an inbound BNSF inspection in the railyard, JRSX 1009 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was observed with incorrect UN numbered corrosive placards that did not match the shipper billing information. As JRSX 1009 was awaiting the application of correct placarding, a BNSF carman observed periodic product drips emanating from its bottom outlet valve (BOV). A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was notified and inspected JRSX 1009. The responder reported that all of the BOV mounting flange bolts on a relatively new BOV mounting flange were less than tool tight (from 3/4 turn to 3 turns loose). The responder tool tightened the four BOV mounting flange bolts and wiped the flange area clean. Afterwards, no further product drips or seepage was evident and the response was concluded by 1230 hrs. PDT, 7/12/08.

column169: PROPER AND SAFE USE OF FORKLIFT, DRUM TRUCK AND PARTS WITH EQUIPMENT! RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. IF ATTACHMENTS USED FOR FORKLIFT ARE IMPROPERLY WORKING, THEY MUST BE REMOVED FROM SERVICE ANDBE REPAIRED OR TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE PERMANENTLY. MAINTENANCE MUST BE DONE PROPERLY TO ENSURE SAFETY USE FORALL. WHEN ENTERING OR EXITING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS, OR TOTES LOADED OR STACKED ON THE FLOOR; ON A PLATFORM AND OR HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCKMUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT.DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING. ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMIC LS,LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS! PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING. LEAVE PAIL OF HAZARDOUS OR CHEMICAL IN THE BAY UNTIL TRAILER IS READY FOR CLOSE. EMPLOYEE GIVEN COACHING ON LOADING AND DOC AWARENESS. APPROPRIATE DISCIPLINE WAS ISSUED.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous arrived at the intended waste management facility and was staged at the receiving dock pending unloading and processing.  During this storage time, facility personnel noticed a small amount of material leaking from the rear of the trailer onto parking area.  Facility personnel activated the facility's emergency response team who donned the appropriate PPE, entered the trailer, and identified a 55 gallon non-bulk package containing individual containers of paint and paint related materials had built pressure that caused the lid to become displaced from the container.  The container in question was placed into a suitable salvage drum and the inside of the trailer and adjoining drums were cleaned with a suitable cleaning compound.  IN addition, a small amount of contaminated solid that was contaminated when the material leaked from the rear of the van trailer was containerized and disposed at the facility.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, the containers were inspected and no visual indicators were observed that would indicate the drum was developing or had developed pressure.  A review of the containers after the incident did not clearly identify a cause of the pressure build-up though it is suspected that one of the inner packages developed pressure caused by the ambient temperature and the agitation of the shipment during transportation.  This, we suspect allowed the accumulation of vapors in the head space of the drum that eventually displaced the lid.    In order to prevent a recurrence, the shipper of the material has been requested to inspect future shipments and insure that all inner containers are secured and sealed to prevent the generation of vapors that could cause an over pressurization of a non-bulk package.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous material arrived at the intended waste management facility and was staged at the receiving dock pending unloading and processing.  During this storage time, facility personnel noticed a small amount of material leaking from the rear of the trailer onto parking area.  Facility personnel activated the facility's emergency response team who donned the appropriate PPE, entered the trailer, and identified a 55 gallon non-bulk package had developed a small pinhole leak in the sidewall of the container.  The container in question was placed into a suitable salvage drum along with all clean-up debris that was collected both from the floor of the van trailer and compacted soil parking area. Once secured, the container and all clean-up debris was disposed of that the facility’s waste disposal area.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, the containers were inspected and no evidence of damage or leaking was observed.  Both the shipper and loading personnel have been advised to insure that each container is thoroughly inspected prior to acceptance and appropriate corrective actions are taken if a container with suspect integrity is observed.

The drum was placed into a suitable salvage drum and the trailer was cleaned with a suitable cleaning compound and all clean-up debris was placed within the salvage drum for proper waste management.  The trailer was unloaded at the facility where the release was identified.

column168: Driver stopped at a rest area and noticed HazMat liquid leaking from both sides of the trailer onto the pavement at a slow rate. The driver notified Mr. bob Mulac of U.S.A. Truck who notified HMHTTC Response, Inc. at 13:49 E.S.T. HMHTTC Response, Inc. dispatched Viva Environmental to the scene to handle the remediation of the incident.     Responders overpacked the leaking drum, neutralized and cleaned the spilled material from the trailer and the approiximatley 15'x15' area of asphalt surface that was affected by the spill. It was 16 hours from the time the incident was reported to the time of completion of the cleanup.

The Tractor and Trailer overturned at low speed on the off  ramp of the highway. Causing therelease of approximatley 5,000 Gallons of diesel fuel. column168: Loader had just begun the first load of acetic anhydride out of R/C CELX 3282. When he walked down the platform, he noticed a steady drip coming from under the railcar. column169: The shipper contacted a local company, Hepaco, to repair the leak. Railcar was emptied as instructed and an investigation is ongoing. The shipper believes that the railcar may have been humped. Facility will continue to inspect inbound railcars for defects and take appropriate action when defects are found.

column168: GATX 29502 was noted by Norfolk Southern's contractor RSI Logistics personnel after removing the bottom outlet valve cap and prior to commencing unloading with product dripping from the bottom outlet valve.   Norfolk Southern's contractor RSI Logistics representatives were unable to stop the release by tighteneing the valve operating handle.    Shipper representatives, Rescar, responded and advised it would be necessary to empty the car and transfer it to a tank car shop for further inspection and repair or replacement of the bottom outlet valve.  Field repair could not be accomplished.    The leak was controlled by reinstalling and tightening the valve cap.  All released material was contained and properly disposed of.  The contents of the car was off-loaded without incident utilizing the top fittings.    The car will be forwarded to a tank car repair facility under FRA Movement Authority 08070229.

The employee was driving a Tractor with a beverage trailer attached.  The trailer contained 20 lb cylinders of propane.  It had just started raining – The employee was exiting the Garden State Pkwy- he  hit the brakes then felt the trailer get wobbly.  Shortly after the employee felt the trailer acting funny then the tractor jerked to the right ending up on the side of the exit ramp upright in the grass.  When the tractor met the trailer the fuel tank was punctured spilling 100 gallons of diesel gasoline.    The Monmouth county Haz Mat was on scene cleaning the fuel  Reported the diesel fuel spill to NJ Dept. of Environmental Protection. 1-877-927-6337 DEP case # 0807081144-38
column169: This accident is being investigated.  If this incident occurred as a result of carelessness, disciplinary actions will be taken.

column168: An Employee was  filling his bobtail (CTMV) and did not put the safety key loop on, walked away from his vehicle while he was filling, shut off the pump, got in the bobtail and drove away before disconnecting the hose.   This damaged the hose and a pipe from the riser. There was no damage to the CTMV.  Approximately 75 gallons of propane release and disbursed into the air immediately.  All of this gas was contained in the storage risers piping/hose.  All safety measures on the riser shut off properly to prevent a larger release of propane.   Everything on the riser was immediately capped and plugged.  Repairs have since been made.
column169: Employees are coached to follow our policies of ignition key control and performing a complete walk-around of the vehicle before moving it. Employees who fail to follow our policies are often times required to write and present a safety meeting to their peers covering the infraction they committed. A pull-away is regarded as a very serious offense, therefore have a greater potential for more severe disciplinary actions.

column168: BNSF track employees working in the railyard near ACFX 82823 (DOT 111A100W1 two compartment tank car) observed product drips emanating from one of the bottom operated bottom outlet valves (BOV). BNSF mechanical responders immediately placed absorbent material under the dripping BOV, which was later replaced by a plastic receptacle. No ground impact from the product drips was evident. The product was seeping from the threaded area around the BOV closure cap. The responders inspected the BOV finding the BOV closure cap snug, but tightened it slightly with a wrench. The BOV handle appeared to have slipped from its fully closed position. The BOV handle was moved to the closed position and the product dripping ceased. A mechanical wedge was inserted between the handle and the locking pin to stabilize the handle in the closed position. ACFX 82823 was released to proceed to its destination at 1130 hrs. CDT, 7/21/08.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

An environmental contractor was dispatched to the scene to assist in the transfer of product to a second tanker. After the original tanker was removed, the area where it came to rest was excavated to remove diesel fuel that had leaked from the saddle tanks. The site was then backfilled and restored to its original conditions.

column168: The totes were sent to delivery to the forwarding agent/broker in Laredo. Upon inspection, 1 tote was found to have liquid around the lid. Two zip ties were placed on lid at time of shipment to prevent tampering and as evidence the containers were still in the condition they were shipped. The zip ties were still in place. This indicated the lid either was not tightened properly at the time of shipping or the lid/closure was bad and did not seal. The shipper sent ABF a new lid, we placed the lid on the tote and shipped the tote back to the shipper. ~~The terminal did not provide the package identification markings. The totes most likely were not spec packages considering the exceptions for combusitlbe liquids and IBCs.
column169: Shipper was notified of problem and acknowledged that the container was most likely shipped without the lid being tightened properly.

column168: A FRA Inspector in the railyard reported UTLX 211753 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) leaking product onto its side shell which appeared to be emanating from the top valve area. After the BNSF was informed of this situation, the nearby shipper was notified and their responder was sent to the site to inspect and secure UTLX 211753. The shipper responder closed both the liquid and vapor valves that were partially open via the valve handles. Also, the closure plugs for the liquid and vapor valves that were hand tight were tool tightened. Afterwards, the product leakage from the liquid valve's closure plug ceased. Response was concluded by approximately Noon, CDT, 7/25/08 and UTLX 211753 was released to proceed to its destination. All spillage evaporated.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

WE DO NOT KNOW HOW LONG THE RELEASE WAS BUT W4E WERE NITIFIED BY ONE OF OUR OTHER DRIVERS COMING UP0N THE SCENE. WE REQUESTED HE BE LET IN TO PUMP OFF THE REMAINING PRODUCT BUT WE WERE HELD  OFF BY PERSONNEL AT THE SCENE FOR 3 HOURS. AT HTAT TIME WE PUMPED OFF THE REMAINING PRODUCT.
column169: OUR COMPANY HAS ROUTED ALL TRUCKS AWAY FROM THIS HIGHWAY. WE NOW REQUIRE ALL TRUCKS TO USE A DIFFERENT ROUTE ADDING EXTRA MILES BUT MUCH SAFER. TRANSPORTATION WISE. column168: Driver said he inspected the cargo tank before taking it to the shipper to load and the washout caps were on and secure.  The trailer was loaded and the loader said he checked the washout cap on the back and middle and they were secure.  Because of the fall protection, he could not reach the front washout cap and asked the driver if it was secure and was told yes.    After loading, the driver drove to the plant scale and product splashed out of the washout port. The cap was found laying on the ground.
column169: It appears that the driver did not properly secure the washout cap before bringing the trailer to load.  The driver has since been brought into the office to receive performance enhancement training in spill prevention.

THE PAIL INSIDE OF THE BOX WAS FOUND LEAKING DUE TO THE LOAD HAD SH1FTED CAUSING THE PAIL TO FALL OVER AND LIQUID TO LEAK OUT. THE PAIL AND AFFECTED MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED  AND LINED SALVAGE DRUMS. THE DRUMS ARE BEING HELD PENDING DISPOSITION.THE FREIGHT WAS TILTED ON THE DECK BARS. column169: BEflER BLOCKING AND BRACING SHOULD BE CONSIDERED WHEN LOADING CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ON DECKBARS. SOMETHING THIS HEAVY SHOULD HAVE PROPABLY BEEN LOADED, ON THE FLOOR AND NOT SUSPENDED IN THE AIR ON DECK BARS.

column169: INSPECT AREAS THOROUGHLY TO ENSURE UNSAFE CONDITIONS ARE NOT PRESENT TO AVOID EASY DAMAGING TO PACKAGES OF DRUMS, PAILS, BAGS AND OTHER PACKAGING CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS OR CHEMICALS. PAILS, BAGS AND DRUMS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICAL AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED TO PREVENT FROM BEING DAMAGED BY   ADJACENT FREIGHT OR SHARP AND POINTED OBJECTS, SUCH AS A NAIL. USE DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD, MTY PALLETS AND OR AIRBAGS TO PROPERLY SHROUD, BLOCK, BRACE AND SECURE FREIGHT AND THE ENTIRE LOAD. column168: NATX 302990 was connected by hoses to a tank truck prior to beginning unloading by RSI Leasing, Inc. personnel .  When the vapor valve was opened liquid product entered the hose under excessive pressure causing the vapor line hose to rupture at the truck connection.    The cause of the failure was overloading of the car allowing liquid product to enter the vapor line due to pressure to build-up.    The tank car and truck were being attended during connection for unloading.  The attendant on the car immediately shut-off the vapor line and the attendant at the truck immediately placed the ruptured hose in a spill pan to contain leakage.  A total of about 2 gallons of product escaped and was contained with absorbent pads.      Note, The "destination" indicated in item 13, 1000 Van Dorn Street, Alexandria, VA, is the final rail destination but is only an intermediate point in transportation.  The car was transloaded into trucks for delivery to the actual final receiver destination(s).  This additional destination information is provided due to the fact the format of this form does not allow the entry of additional consignee information.
column169: RSI Leasing, Inc. personnel have contacted the shipper to advise them not to overload cars in the future.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. Driver was delivering gasoline to a customer. The driver got veeder reading to verify tank sizes. There were two, 10000 gallon tanks. The driver did not follow procedure and made the assumption that the 6500 gallons he was delivering would fit. While unloading the driver noticed that fuel began to leak. The driver immediately shut off flow of product but approximately 10 gallons leaked into the concrete containment area. The driver, with the assistance of lead dispatcher, was able to clean-up the spill to the client's satisfaction. David Cerulo, with Hess management verified this.
column169: Driver failed to follow Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. unloading procedures. This driver was counseled on proper procedures and it was determined that the driver was not understanding what was required and therefore was terminated.

column168: After loading, our driver returned to our terminal where the trailer was discovered to be leaking from underneath in front of the trailer tandems.  The load was then transferred into another trailer at the terminal.  Most of the spilled material was caught in a 5 gallon bucket that was placed underneath the leak.    Trailer was cleaned and sent to an outside shop for tests to locate the leak's origin.  Trailer was found to have cracked at the ring area front of the tandem on the left side of the cargo tank.
column169: Continue due diligence with the testing of the trailers in addition to pressure testing the trailers before they go load.  The weakness with the pressure test is that in most cases, a stress crack will not show itself until the tank is loaded and the weight of the material opens the crack up.

column168: KAG Tank Services was in the process of repairing a tank-truck for Brown’s Oil Service. An employee of KAG Tank Services opened a valve on the trailer and was unaware there was diesel fuel still being held in the tank. As a result, approximately 326 gallons of diesel fuel was able to be released. A majority of the spilled diesel was captured by the site’s oil-water separator. A small portion of the diesel was able to make it to soil. ERS Environmental has responded to the site and handled the remediation. The contaminated soil has been removed and the oil-water separator has been pumped out. No further environmental impact is expected.
column169: KAG Tank Services will implement further procedures to be certain that a tank is empty prior to opening any valves.

Driver was transporting miscellaneous hazardous waste such as shredded drums, etc.  The waste is rinsed down before shipment and the dump trailer is parked at a incline in a drain area of the shipper to drain off any excess liquid before the driver picks up the trailer. Driver stopped at a truck stop enroute and noticed a small drip coming from the back of the dump trailer. He put a bucket under it.  He also noticed that a section of the gasket looked out of place.  We called out a emergency response vendor to assist in getting the back gate of the truck open enough to secure the gasket and collect any liquid that might come out in the process.  Gasket was successfully replaced to control any leakage.
column169: The trailer had just recently (before the incident) been inspected and the gasket replaced.  The trailer is still at the maintenance shop awaiting inspection to see why the gasket failed.

column168: Driver was picking up a loaded cargo tank that was being relayed in our yard.  Upon doing her pre-trip, she noticed a drip coming from underneath the trailer near the front.  She put a bucket under it.  We weren't sure whether or not rainwater had gotten into the insulation or if it was product.  Considering this was a poison, we erred on the side of safety and transferred the product to another trailer.  We had an emergency response crew stand by in case of any incidents.  The transfer was completed successfully. (note:  the UN# on the BOL is UN3426.  This program would not recognize that number. I had to enter UN2074 which is acrylamide solid to continue processing this report.  This product is acrylamide solution, UN3426.)
column169: The cargo tank was brought into the shop and inspected.  It was found that the front washout cap had a damaged neck and did not seal properly.  This allowed product to seap out around the barrel and through the skin.  The neck was resurfaced and a new gasket installed to prevent further leakage.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. driver was in transit, loaded, ready to deliver unleaded gas to a customer location. As the driver was coming off of an entrance ramp, approaching I-85 in Montgomery, a driver attempted to pass on the right of our vehicle. The car attempting to pass our truck sideswiped the trailer. The crash resulted in damage to our tractor and trailer. The trailer damage included breaking our loading head. The resulted in a 5-10 gallon spill. The spill was contained with spill pads on the concrete roadway, not reaching soil or drains. The remaining product was transfered to another unit for delivery.
column169: Other drivers on the roadway need to be aware of their surrounding. The other driver appeared to attempt to drive into a lane that did not exist. The driver of the other car involved in this accident was charged with careless driving, among other offenses.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. Driver was delivering fuel to a retail client location. While unloaded the driver noticed that the hose jumped. Driver turned off compartment hand valve, climbed on top of the trailer and opening the dome lid to get a stick reading on remaining product. As driver was looking down he noticed that fuek was leaking out of the drop fitting and slowly forming a puddle. Driver immediately got down and began to contain spill. Haines City Police and Fire Department responded. The spill was cleaned up, being contained all on concrete, not reaching soil or drains. The cuase of the spill was investigated, it was determined that when the driver turned off the hand valve, he did not close the handle. When he opened the dome lid, it created pressure which pushed fuel out of a loose fitting.
column169: Driver did not follow proper unloading procedures, nor was dispatch notified when he started to encounter problems. Driver was counseled on unloading procedures but following the spill investigation the driver was terminated. Had proper procedures been followed, spill would not have occured.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. driver was delivering nitric acid to a client location. Upon the completion of his delivering the driving was putting away his hoses when he noticed product leaking from the top of the storage tank. Driver immediately started to contain the spill, but approximately 10-15 gallons leaked into the containment area. No product reached soil or drains. The plant engineer came and observed the area, noting that there was no damage and all was clean to his satisfaction. They also would be investigating the tank to determine the cause of the leak, as the product was not overfilled.
column169: The customer was advised of the faulty tank and would be repairing prior to any future deliveries. The tank will be inspected by internal safety personnel prior to delivery as well.

column168: On July 20, 2008, at approximately 0720 hours, a railway tankcar GATX 51952, loaded with Ammonia, Anhydrous,non-flammable gas, UN1005 was reported leaking at the Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) Mossville Louisiana yard. The tank car was discovered leaking from the pressure relief device. The shipper representative responded to the site replacing the pressure relief O ring. There were no injuries, no damage to the environment.        CODE: 414  NARRI: 5(5+1+1)x(2+0)=60
column169: On The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR), shippers are immediately notified of all HAZMAT releases.  For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package or closure defects), where possible, shippers (responsible party) are requested to respond, repair and remediate.  By immediately involving the shipper, in-depth knowledge of the release cause is gained by the same organization that can implement process changes to prevent recurrence.  After each NAR incident, KCSR provides outreach to the shipper to help investigate root-cause factors for correction.  For non-accident related releases, the shipper should be contacted directly for details associated with actions taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: Employees at the Union Pacific rail yard at Livonia, LA reported the release of hazardous materials from three tank cars. The tank cars HOKX 111204, GATX 22291 and HOKX 111309, loads of potassium hydroxide solution, had released product from one or more of the valves on the top of the tanks. Thomas Robinson, Manager Hazardous Materials inspected the tank cars.  Each car had released less than a quart of product from its respective PRDs.  The valves displayed no apparent defects and they were not releasing product at this time.  The shipper, Occidental Chemical, was contacted and arrangements were made for their representatives to inspect the cars.  The cars were decontaminated, pressure and outage checked, and released.
column169: Re-test PRD's.

column168: Fuel Truck was traveling south on KY15 as it approached the Ky 160 intersection a coal truck pulled out infront of him across KY15. He had to swerve behind the coal truck to avoid a collision. The fuel inside the tank shifted and caused the vehicle to become unstable. The driver lost control of the tanker wchich overturned onto the guardrail which ripped the seams of the tank allowing the fuel to leak when the truck & tank came to rest on the passenger side in the center of the highway. The fuel leaked out for approximately 3 hours. First responders & in house clean up personel made a dam below the culvert to contain product reaching Smoot Creek. They also made a sand barrier along the guardrail allowing the fuel to pool & be sucked up off the roadway. The professional clean up crew arrived & took control of clean up.
column169: State should install traffic signals at this intersection.

column168: Subject shipment was part of a consolidated load from Kelly Global Logistic INC (i.e. the freight forwarder) to Seaboard Marine (i.e. the carrier). Based on information from the freight forwarder, Parallel Refrigeration INC (i.e. the shipper) loaded 12 fibreboard boxes containing UN 3337 (Refrigerant Gas R 404A) into the subject container without delclaring it as hazardous materials.    Upon notification from the freight forwarder, the carrier placed the shipment on hold until the shipment could be rendered compliant. Subsequently, proper documentation was provided to the carrier, who then placarded the freight container accordingly. Thus, the shipment hold was rescinded and the container was ultimately transported to its final destination.     // END OF REPORT //

column168: At approximately 6:25 am on 07/21/08 Gordon Co Fire Dept Lt. Rex Lowe notified our company that there had been a leak on the road leaving our plant. At that time we were notified by our driver of this spill. At 6:38 am we notified Mr. Bert Langley's office with the GA EPD. At 7:10 our branch manager Mr. Jim Novak arrived on the scene and was met by Lt. Rex Lowe and several others from Gordon Co. EMS including EMA Deputy Director Richard Cooper. Marion Environmental was called to clean up. They arrived at 8:30 am and completed clean up by 12:30 pm.  Investigation found that the relief valve on back of tanker #1639 had popped off from pressure in the tanker. Vent valves are kept open on tankers until the driver is ready to leave the plant. What the driver didn't notice as he left was that the auto valve on top of the tanker had closed. This valve supplies air when open. Since it closed the pressure built up popping the relief valve off.
column169: Drivers were re-trained on tankers and relief valves and what built up pressure will do. Review of the new pre-trip checklist to include checking the top auto valve on tankers.

column168: On 07/24/08 driver Rashad Thompson was taking his load of muratic acid to Manatee Chemical. At 0900 as he made his turn one of the drums containing 30x1 gallon jugs tipped over. Driver saw smoke coming out from his flatbed and pulled over and saw a small amount of acid had leaked out on his flatbed. Driver notified the plant and immediately a response team was dispatched. Upon arrival we noticed that the Manatee County Fire Department was already on the scene and in the process of cleaning up the spill. Officer in charge of the Fire Department was Bob Tollise. Mr. Tollise stated that no report would be written up by the Fire Department. No bottles came out of the drum and no caps were off the bottles. It was determined that about one half gallon of acid had leaked out of a combination of 3 loose gallon jug caps.

column168: Drum was loaded next to trailer wall and secured using adjustible cargo strap. Other freight to the left of drum was stable and all was rear loaded. Strap failed during transit and allowed the bottom of the drum to walk off the skid. Drum then leaned against the rear trailer door at an angle that allowed loss of product at the drum head area. No apparant impact damage to the drum head, gasket leaked.  Third party mitigation to secure leak and recover spill material from trailer floor and concrete shoulder of the road. Minimal soil contamination. Excavation and testing performed. All spill materials placed in recovery and transported from the scene for proper classification and disposal by 3P spill mitigation.
column169: Placement of air bag dunnage at the lower area of the drums may have prevented the drum from movement when the strap failed. Cargo strap was in good condition when loaded and product secured. Unknown cause of strap failure.

column168: Operator was unloading rail car PLMX 35304, when the pressure relief valve discharged for 2-3 seconds, causing a brief release of vapor. The Operator immediately shut down the compressor and halted the unloading process. He then called the corporate office to report the incident. It was determined that the excess flow valve had closed, and that the operator did not hear it, thus causing the slight release of vapor. The unloading process was completed without further incident. The estimated release was less than 1 pound of vapor. No evacuations were made and no injuries were reported.

column168: On July 29, 2008, USES personnel arrived on site at approximately 1145 ET.  They determined that the 5 gallon pails of material were damaged due to improper loading.  The pails were loaded on pallets and one pallet was placed on top of another, so that there were two layers.  The contractor stated that the weight must have been too great for the pails on the bottom, which caused them to crack and release material.  The material was contained in the back of the trailer and did not impacted the environmental or asphalt parking surface in any way.  The contractor removed the pallets from the trailer and sorted through them to determine which ones had been damaged.  The damaged pails were placed in a roll off box and transported for disposal.  The contractor then used granular absorbents to remove the material from the trailer floor.  The pails were repacked on pallets and loaded back into the trailer.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE TRAVELING, THE TERRA INDUSTRIES, INC. TRUCK WAS STRUCK BY A PASSENGER VEHICLE, WHICH CAUSED THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 2,300 GALLONS OF UREA AMMONIUM NITRATE SOLUTION. THE FREE PRODUCT MIGRATED DOWN THE SOIL EMBANKMENT ADJACENT TO THE HIGHWAY. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE. ENVIRONMENTAL SOLUTIONS, INC. OF OMAHA, NEBRASKA WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. UPON ARRIVAL ON SITE, ENVIRONMENTAL SOLUTIONS, INC. APPLIED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO THE FREE LIQUID ALONG THE ROADWAY, AND SECURED THE SITE, PENDING LOCATION OF UTILITY LINES. ENVIRONMENTAL SOLUTIONS, INC. RETURNED TO THE SITE THE FOLLOWING DAY TO EXCAVATE THE IMPACTED SOIL. THE FREE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE SOIL, AND DID NOT MIGRATE INTO ANY ROADSIDE DITCHES OR STORM SEWERS IN THE AREA. NO WATERWAYS WERE AFFECTED BY THE RELEASE. ENVIRONMENTAL SOULUTIONS, INC. CONTAINERIZED APPROXIMATELY 100 TONS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL, WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED TO LOCAL FARM, PENDING BIOREMEDIATION. SITE WAS RESTORED TO PREEXISTING CONDITION. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.
column169: SINCE THE RELEASE WAS ACCIDENTAL, AND APPEARS TO BE THE RESULT OF THIRD PARTY NEGLIGENCE, NO PLANS EXIST TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. TERRA INDUSTRIES, INC. WILL CONTINUE TO REINFORCE SAFE HANDLING PROCEDURES AND DRIVER SAFETY TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column169: SECUREMENT OF PAILS ON PALLETS! DRUMS AND OR PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT. THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND OR MTY PALLETS. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO END PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED. RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDMATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS,PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT. DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. FREIGHT MUST SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column169: DISCUSS WITH THE SHIPPER ON THE IMPORTANCE OF MAKING SURE PACKAGING TOTES CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS,CHEMICALS AND LIQUID MUST BE SAFE FOR TRANSPORTING AND TRAVELING. LIDS AND OTHER CLOSURES MUST BE TIGHT TOPREVENT LIDS FROM LOOSENING, RELEASING THE LIQUID. THE DURABILITY OF A TOTE MUST BE ABLE MAINTAIN AND CONTAIN THE LIQUIDS OR POWDERS FROM SEAPING OUT. IT IS IMPORTANT THAT TOTES ARE CHECKED BY SHIPPER AND TESTED TO ENSURE THAT PACKAGE DETERIORATION HAS NOT OCCURRED. IMPORTANT THAT LIDS AND TOPS OF PACKAGES ARE SECURED A TIGHTENED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE. TOTES AND DRUMS WITH VALVES MUST BE SAFELY CLOSED AND THE CONTAINER,PACKAGING, MUST BE DURABLE TO ENSURE NO LIQUID OR POWDER IS ALLOWED TO BE RELEASED. DISCUSS WITH SHIPPER ON PROPER, SAFE AND RELIABLE PACKAGING TO PREVENT EASY RELEASE OF PRODUCT. PACKAGING OF CHEMICALS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND LIQUIDS MUST BE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED BEFORE IT LEAVES ORIGIN!

column168: Swift Transportation contacted Emergency Response & Training Solutions (ERTS)to oversee and manage environmental operations. A tracter trailer carrying approximately 80 cubic yards of asbestos had several bags broken during transportation, the broken bags resulted from possible shipper error due to improper packaging.  WMS secured the trailer, prepared the trailer for access and removed all broken or unbroken bags from the trailer. column168: Barnett Transportation Inc. driver was attempting to unload JP-8 jet fuel at Massachusetts National Guard FMS, Worcester, MA. by utilizing his PTO pump. After making all necessary hose connections, driver was assured by Guard personnel that all valves to the receiving tank was openand ready to receive product. Driver engaged PTO pump to begin unloading process. Driver realized he did not have product flow and was attempting to disengage the PTO pump when the discharge hose ruptured causing a spill of approximately 40 gallons of JP-8 Jet Fuel. Subsequently, it was dis-covered that a valve on the receiving tank line was not opened by personnel assisting with the unloading process.Sgt. Eva Brown (508-791-8257) notified Massachusetts DEP. Michael Schere w/ Tighe & Bond, Environmental Consulting Engineers, responded.(508) 754-2201 (508) 471-9624 Photos & Soil Samples Taken.Environmental Contact DEP - Elizabeth Sauer, (508) 233-6696-

column168: A BNSF crew switching rail cars at the Pasco/Tidewater rail terminal reported a chemical odor emanating from DCLX 3057 (DOT 105J500W tank car). DCLX 3057 was isolated at a Tidewater industrial track.  Three BNSF employees (crew members whom reported this odor) were taken to a local hospital for evaluation and examination for chemical vapor exposure. All three were examined and released, although two of these crew members had x-rays taken that resulted in negative findings and medical prescriptions provided. Two of the three crew members incurred lost work days afterwards.  BNSF contract responders were called to provide air monitoring support, product decontamination and inspection of DCLX 3057. Responders found all external valves and fittings secure. A small amount of dampness was found at the base of the A-end liquid valve and it was wiped dry. Also, a dried stain that originated near the valve housing area and ran down the side of the tank shell at center tank was cleaned. Afterwards, DCLX 3057 was carefully moved a very short distance to its unloading location at the Tidewater facility. Once DCLX 3057 was unloaded, the contract responders pressured-up the tank to 7-8 psi and this pressure held for over two hours. No root cause for the product vapor odor could be readily determined.   SA-080802 received to transport residue DCLX 3057 to a specialized cleaning facility.  In late September, 2008 the railcar cleaning facility's preliminary testing at 30 psi indicated that the A-end liquid valve leaked through the ball. This valve is scheduled for tear-down for root cause analysis at a later date at a qualified tank car repair facility.  The last tank qualification for DCLX 3057 was accomplished in the year of 2005.

column169: A CONTINUED EDUCATION PROGRAM TO HELP ENSURE PROPER LOADING PRACTICES.  A REINTRODUCTION OF THE PRACTICE OF USING DUNNAGE TO BLOCK AND BRACE FREIGHT. column168: On Thursday July 24, 2008 at approximately 4:15 PM EDT, Savage’s Transfer Operator - Bryheem Berry setup and was conducting a Solvay HFS tank car to tank trailer preload transfer.  The transfer originated from Solvay tank car ACFX 77590 and was expected to transfer 40,000 LBS/4,000 GALS into Quality Carriers acid tank trailer #50119.  The Solvay tank car ACFX 77590, and QC trailer # 50119 were spotted and staged approximately in the middle of the terminal’s transfer track # 8 and corresponding asphalt aisle way.    Mr. Berry setup the transfer on the tank car side by applying the liquid product valve assembly fitting, applying air fitting/adapter, connecting compressed air hose and liquid product transfer hose.  Mr. Berry then proceeded to setup the trailer side by inserting the discharge end of the transfer hose into the trailer’s open dome and secured it by wrapping a bungee cord around the hose and tying it down by the dome lid housing.  Mr. Berry then proceeded to set the depth indicator on the depth stick by utilizing the trailer’s outage chart and order quantity.  Upon completion of the setup process, Mr. Berry proceeded to commence the transfer by opening the tank car’s product primary and secondary liquid valves and pressurizing the tank car with compressed air.  Mr. Berry then viewed the product flowing into the trailer, and did not see any abnormalities, nor did he observe evidence of leakage and/or any other issues with either the hose connections and/or containers (tank car; tank trailer).    At approximately 4:45 PM, the QC trailer # 50119 contained 39,100 LBS/3,910 GALS HFS when the bungee cord which previously secured the discharge end of the transfer hose came undone from the trailer’s dome lid housing and the transfer hose dislodged from the inside the trailer.  Mr. Berry who was on the ground level at the time, immediately ascended the tank car’s ladder and shutoff the car’s product primary and secondary liquid valves.      Approximately 50 gallons of Solvay HFS were released from the transfer hose; the spillage predominantly accumulated onto the underlying asphalt pavement, and minute amounts seeped into the adjacent ballast area, as well as accumulated within the corresponding tank cars' track pan.  No injuries were sustained from this incident.  Onsite personnel responded promptly to the incident scene, they contained/diked the spillage, protected the integrity of the storm drain system and neutralized the spill with sodium bicarbonate/soda ash.  The soda ash HFS mixture then was shoveled up, along with the affected ballast areas and drummed.  Prompt notifications were made to TRANSFLO’s Mgt, CSXT Philly Eastside personnel (Tim McBride), CSX Police, National Response Center (Report # 878379), PADEP and the City of Philadelphia.    By 6:00 PM, Savage personnel wrapped up response and clean up activities.  React Environmental (Emergency Response/Environmental Contractor) is expected this week (8/4 - 8/8) to complete the corresp
column169: Corrective Action(s)  The below items have been identified as the corresponding corrective actions which shall be implemented in order to prevent this incident from reoccurring.     1) Utilize on all future HFS transfer a 2” loading tube on the trailer side that that can be inserted into the trailer’s open dome way and secured by the dome lid’s ears.  The 10 micron drawstring filter sock shall also be applied to the loading tube’s discharge spout and secured with a band clamp.  This transfer method enhancement was implemented on 7/25/2008.    2) Savage’s Regional Management shall survey the other Savage operated TRANSFLO terminals to inquire whether there are any splash tank car to tank truck transfers or vise versa which utilize bungee cords to secure a transfer hose that is inserted down either inside a trailer’s open dome and/or tank car’s open manway.  The survey results shall be evaluated upon a case by case basis with the intent to make potential enhancements (e.g., progressing towards a hard connection/loading tube) depending upon the transfer method and gauging of product/outage.  Expected Completion Date: 9/30/2008

column168: Transport vehicle operated by TransWood Inc. stopped on designated route at mandatory fuel stop. Truck drivers noticed a mist rising from the manifold cabinet at rear of trailer. Drivers located vehicle away from persons as practical, notified dispatch of leak, and called 911, evacuated the vehicle with shipping documents and HM information. TransWood notified MEMC and PCS of leaking trailer. MEMC dispatched Eagle Environmental (contracted response) to the site. Police, fire and ambulance responded. TransWood personnel were not allowed in the area to record events or gather information, and the site was handled upon arrival by Eagle Environmental.  MEMC indicates the following causes of failure:  1) Leak through #2 tube isolation valve, through the 1 1/2’ feed valve and through the valve cap.  2) Defective air operated valve failed to hold the #2 tube closed  3) Defective valve stop prevented the 1 112” valve from sealing closed  4) Defective threads on hose cap prevented hose cap from sealing  Estimated release of 1258 lbs to atmosphere.
